      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A month after Sept. 11, America, with the help of Britain, has struck Afghanistan in a war against terrorism. Afghan-Americans are torn. This action may be necessary in the war against terrorism, but it will kill innocent people.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A month after Sept. 11, America, with the help of Britain, has struck Afghanistan in a war against terrorism. Afghan-Americans are torn. This action may be necessary in the war against terrorism, but it will kill innocent people.</p>
        <p>Yet in the long run, the strikes on Afghanistan will mean the destruction of the Taliban, and this will mean that Afghanistan can become a civilized nation again.</p>
        <p>There is not a day that goes by that most Afghans are not sitting and waiting for news about Afghanistan -- first, during the Soviet occupation, then with the Taliban. It was once my home.</p>
        <p>As the news unfolds, Afghan-Americans wait. They express their reactions only when asked and mourn for two countries: Afghanistan, from which they claim their ethnicity, and America, their home and safe haven.</p>
        <p>MIZGON ZAHIR  Fremont, Calif., Oct. 7, 2001</p>
      </block>
